  1. Get a frequency breakdown of the number of chicks, their average weight and the standard deviation of the weights in each of the diets at the start of the study. Store the resulting data frame in a variable named weight0 and print.
dat1 <- ChickWeight %>% filter(Time == 0)
weight0 <- group_by(dat1, Diet) %>% summarize(n=n(), Mean = mean(weight), StandardDeviation = sd(weight))
print(weight0)
## # A tibble: 4 x 4

extra credit: construct a ggplot that shows average weights by diet with an interval (shown as a line) of +- the standard deviation around the averages

plot <- ggplot(weight0, aes(x=Diet, y = Mean)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=Mean-StandardDeviation, ymax=Mean+StandardDeviation))
plot

  1. Each chick should have twelve weight measurements. Use the dplyr package to identify how many measurements are there for each chick. Extract a subset of the data for all chicks with complete information, name the data set complete, and print the first 3 rows. (Hint: you might want to use mutate to introduce a helper variable consisting of the number of observations)
check_comp <- group_by(ChickWeight, Chick) %>% summarise(n = n())
check_vec <- check_comp %>% filter(n == max(check_comp$n)) %>% pull(Chick)
complete <- ChickWeight %>% filter(Chick %in% check_vec)
print(complete[0:3, ])
##   weight Time Chick Diet
## 1     42    0     1    1
## 2     51    2     1    1
## 3     59    4     1    1
  1. In the complete data set introduce a new variable that measures the current weight difference compared to day 0. Name this variable weightgain and print the first 3 rows of the new data frame.
complete <- group_by(complete, Chick) %>% arrange(Chick, Time) %>% mutate(weightgain = weight - first(weight))
print(complete[0:3, ])
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
## # Groups:   Chick [1]
##   weight  Time Chick Diet  weightgain
##    <dbl> <dbl> <ord> <fct>      <dbl>
## 1     41     0 13    1              0
## 2     48     2 13    1              7
## 3     53     4 13    1             12
  1. Use {ggplot2} to create side-by-side boxplots of weightgain by Diet for day 21. Change the order of the categories in the Diet variable such that the boxplots are ordered by median weightgain, and the lower limit of the y axis should be 0. Describe the relationship in 2-3 sentences.
dat2 <- complete %>% filter(Time == 21)
plot1 <- ggplot(dat2, aes(x=reorder(Diet, weightgain, FUN = median), y = weightgain)) + geom_boxplot() +ylim(0,350) + xlab("Diet number")
plot1

Diet 1 has the least effect with the least median and diet 3 has the most effect with the highest median. Diet 4 has the smallest range of weightgain.

  1. For the chicks with the least and the most weight at time 0, plot their growth trajectories over time. 
most_chick <-group_by(complete, Time) %>% filter(Time == 0) %>% mutate(max_weight = max(weight)) %>% filter(weight == max_weight) %>% pull(Chick)
least_chick <- group_by(complete, Time) %>% filter(Time == 0) %>% mutate(min_weight = min(weight)) %>% filter(weight == min_weight) %>% pull(Chick)
dat3 <- complete %>% filter(Chick %in% most_chick)
dat4 <- complete %>% filter(Chick %in% least_chick)
plot2 <- ggplot(dat3, aes(x= Time, y = weightgain)) + geom_point(aes(color = Chick)) + geom_line(aes(color = Chick))
plot3 <- ggplot(dat4, aes(x= Time, y = weightgain)) + geom_point(aes(color = Chick)) + geom_line(aes(color = Chick))
plot2

plot3

  1. Add to the previous plot the average growth trajectory for all chicks (calculated as the mean weight for each chick at each time). How do the trajectories compare?
dat5 <- group_by(complete, Time) %>% summarise(mean = mean(weightgain))
plot2 + geom_smooth(data = dat5, aes(x=Time, y = mean, color ="mean"), se=F) +ylim(0,300)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
